Page.create!(
  name: 'About us',
  language: 'en',
  category: 'about',
  slug: 'about-us',
  content: <<~ABOUT
  <h1>About us</h1>
  <h2>ANSEL</h2>
  <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">ANSEL association (Association de Nettoyage au Service de l'Environnement et du Littoral) is born in march 2000. They organize coastal clean up, inform about marine waste origin and ecological impacts and raise public awareness  about coastal. Ansel created an </span><a href="https://www.facebook.com/groups/279818875502438" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="font-size: 14px;" target="_blank">observation network</a><span style="font-size: 14px;">, which has now more than 1000 users on Facebook. After the creation of this group, the need for a map to track the many observations collected <span style="font-size: 14px;">becomes obvious</span>. The first steps of this project comes with the collaboration of </span><a href="https://www.we-explore.org/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Roland Jourdain's organization, <span style="font-size: 14px;">Explore</span></span></a><span style="font-size: 14px;"><span style="font-size: 14px;">. The first version of</span> this map is created during the 2016 Ocean Hackathon taking place in Brittany, France.</span>
  </p>
  <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">assoansel @ icloud.com, <a href="https://assoansel.jimdo.com/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Ansel website</a></span></p>
  <h2>Sea-Mer</h2>
  <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">Sea-Mer association was created in 2016 in Wimereux in Pas de Calais, France by long-time waste collectors with the aim of classifying marine litter, to better understand stranding phenomena and marine litter sources. Sea-Mer created and maintains the </span><a href="http://dechets-marins.ovh" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Wikidechets</span></a><span style="font-size: 14px;">, a <span style="font-size: 14px;">marine litter</span> online encyclopedia. Sea-Mer is co-administrator of Ocean Plastic Tracker.</span>
  </p>
  <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">contact @ sea-mer.org, <a href="https://sea-mer.org" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Sea-mer website</a>, </span><a href="https://www.facebook.com/SeaMerAsso/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Facebook</span></a></p>
  <h2>Developers</h2>
  <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">The first version of Ocean Plastic Tracker was launched at the Ocean Hackathon in Brest in October 2016. The open sourced web application was developed in 48 hours, by a team of four developers: <span style="font-size: 14px;">Franck Kerbiriou, <span style="font-size: 14px;">Marc Douchement, </span></span>Pierre Charpentier, et Caroline Geiser. The team is continuing its efforts today to make the application more reliable, more practical and more user-friendly for both <span style="font-size: 14px;">observers and </span>administrators. A version 2, completely re-developed, was put online in April 2019 and continues to be improved. Development is open to all, do not hesitate to contact us or to check out the code on </span><a href="https://github.com/FranckKe/mersea" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Github</span></a><span style="font-size: 14px;">.</span></p>
  <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">contact @ dev.oceanplastictracker.com, </span><a href="https://github.com/FranckKe/mersea" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Mersea on Github</span></a></p>
  <h2>Explore organization</h2>
  <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">The Explore Fund was created under the impulse of the French navigator Roland Jourdain, twice winner of the Route du Rhum, in 2006 and 2010. Explore is an endowment fund, designed to identify and support people working on <span style="font-size: 14px;">innovative </span>solutions to <span style="font-size: 14px;"> social and environmental problems</span>. Explore helped Lionel Lucas of ANSEL to support the project.</span>
  </p>
  <p><a href="https://www.we-explore.org/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Explore website</span></a><span style="font-size: 14px;">, <a href="https://www.facebook.com/fondsexplore/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Facebook</a>, </span><a href="https://twitter.com/FondsExplore?lang=en" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Twitter</span></a></p>
ABOUT
)

Page.create!(
  name: 'Plastic in the sea',
  language: 'en',
  category: 'information',
  slug: 'plastic-in-the-sea',
  content: <<~ABOUT
    <h1>The 1st lung of the planet is sick of plastic</h1>
    <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">More than 300 millions tons of plastic are produced each year worldwide and 8 million tons end up in the oceans [1]. Plastics make up 90% of the ocean's floating waste and 80% of the waste comes from land-based sources via rainwater, rivers, rivers and wind. The rest of the waste comes from economic activities at sea: merchant marine, exploitation of natural resources, off-shore platforms, fishing activities, breeding, yachting, etc.</span></p>
    <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">Our coastline is particularly affected by waste from maritime traffic: 80% of world trade is by sea and 70% of the world's maritime traffic passes off Brittany and the Channel. Oil spills have often caused great damage but the pollution of the oceans by the loss of container is too often underestimated: between October 2013 and March 2014 there are more than 800 containers lost between Cape Finisterre and Ouessant when the experts announce the loss of about 2000 containers a year worldwide. [2]</span></p>
    <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">Observers of drifting waste are more and more numerous in France and in the World. A thousand of them, reunited around the association Ansel de Concarneau, share their observations and investigate the source of the waste they find on their beaches. The comparison of their observations makes it possible to detect abnormal strandings that may be linked to these losses of containers at sea. Ocean Plastic Tracker makes it possible to record all this information to better understand the geographical spread of this waste, but also that of other waste of which the sources are more atypical.</span></p>
    <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">[1] Source: United Nations Environment Program</span></p>
    <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">[2] Source: World Shipping Council</span></p>
    <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">Photos/diagrams: https://atlas-transmanche.certic.unicaen.fr/en/page-255.html, https://gcaptain.com/how-many-shipping-containers-lost-at-sea/</span></p>
  ABOUT
)

