Page.create!(
  name: 'Security',
  language: 'en',
  category: 'information',
  slug: 'security',
  content: <<~SECURITY
    <h1>Security and best practices as a cleaning volunteer</h1>
    <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">Voluntary and spontaneous beach cleaning operations are gradually developing. This practice is within the reach of all, but beware: this is not a trivial activity!</span></p>
    <h2>I put on gloves and do not empty containers</h2>
    <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">Some wastes are sharp or can be contaminated with hydrocarbons and dangerous products. Wear good quality gloves! You never know what bottles, flasks and other cans can hold. By emptying them you can spread dangerous products and risk coming into contact with them.</span></p>
    <h2>I secure dangerous objects and do not touch explosives</h2>
    <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">Explosives must be marked to prevent accidents. They must not be manipulated. Distress flares or smoke can also be dangerous. Call the police for further instructions (17 in france). Hazardous objects such as syringes and sharp objects should be secured in a resistant container. S<span style="font-size: 14px;">yringes can be recycled, please bring them to a dedicated point (</span></span><a href="https://www.cyclamed.org/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><span style="font-size: 14px;">CYCLAMED</span></span></a><span style="font-size: 14px;"><span style="font-size: 14px;"> for example in France)</span></span>
    </p>
    <h2>I inform myself of the tide and do not walk at the bottom of cliffs</h2>
    <p><span style="font-size: 14px;">Always check tide times, and once on site, monitor water level. Some areas quickly become inaccessible. Watch out for rocks falling, mudslides and landslides as they are common and unpredictable. Keep a reasonable distance, even if you do not pick up trash near the cliffs. </span></p>
    <h2>I preserve the dunes and do not trample the vegetation </h2>
    <p>Vegetation is fragile. It can suffer trampling and be damaged when dragging bulky waste. The path in the vegetation must therefore be avoided. Dunes constitute a particularly fragile environment sometimes strongly subjected to the erosion of the wind and the sea. Walking on dunes weakens them. Even if you find waste on dunes, picking it up should be avoided.</p>
    <h2>I avoid nesting areas and I do not disturb birds</h2>
    <p>The beach is a resting place for many birds where some find food and sometimes a place to nest. It is important to learn about nesting times and areas near local associations and to avoid them. The beach wrack is one of the favorite place for sea birds to feed. It is important to be careful of it and not to disturb the birds that might be eating.</p>
    <p>If you find a banded bird, you can contact the <a href="https://crbpo.mnhn.fr/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">CRBPO</a> and you will participate in follow-ups made around the world.</p>
    <h2>I drop picked up garbage in dedicated containers</h2>
    <p>In the absence of a trashcans, it is necessary to avoid leaving waste at the entrance of beaches or car parks. Trash bags will be likely never picked up and content might spread. If there is too much, you can call town technical services.</p>
    <h2>I report pollutants in unusual quantities</h2>
    <p>In case of discovery of pollutants such as oil or paraffin, the ideal is to call the police (17 in France). Some beaches have already been polluted for some time. Local beach cleaning associations can help you determine if the beaching you saw is new or old.</p>
    <h2>If I see an animal in difficulty or a dead animal</h2>
    <p>If you discover a dolphin, a whale or a seal, that it is in difficulty or dead, do not approach them and inform the national center <a href="http://www.observatoire-pelagis.cnrs.fr/participez/signaler-un-echouage-257/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">PELAGIS</a> in +33 5 46 44 99 10, even on Sunday. All instructions to know and follow are on <a href="http://www.observatoire-pelagis.cnrs.fr/participez/signaler-un-echouage-257/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">their website</a></p>
    <p>If you see a bird in difficulty or injured, contact a <a href="http://www.ufcs.fr" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">UFCS</a> center or the nearest <a href="https://www.lpo.fr" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">LPO center</a>. They will advise you on the steps to follow. </p>
    <h2>I observe marine litter and I get to know them</h2>
    <p>Not all marine litter is alike. Some of them deserve special attention as they can come from far away or be unusual. Passionate collectors keep a collection of their most unique waste.</p>
    <p>To dive into these mysteries and know the origin of the waste you collect, <a href="http://dechets-marins.ovh" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Wiki-déchet</a> can help you.</p>
    <p>Enjoy beach cleaning and do not forget: when the beach is clean, it is most likely that the waste is in the water, or that they were collected!</p>
    <p>Source: <a href="https://oceanplastictracker.com/system/files/security.pdf">10 bons réflexes pour une bonne pratique du nettoyage de plage bénévole</a> by Jonathan Henichart, Sea-Mer Asso</p>
  SECURITY
)

